<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
  Experiment 4 — SWArch Metamodel Extension + ATL Generation
  Complexity: Very High

  THE CORE PROBLEM:
    The current SWArch metamodel cannot express deployment triggers, retry
    policies, or manual approval gates. Those concepts exist in the PIM
    metamodel (PushTrigger, ManualTrigger, Job.maxAttempts) and in the GitLab
    PSM (GitlabRule, Retry, when:manual) — but swarch2pim never generates them
    because SWArch has no fields to drive that generation.

    This SWArch model below uses THREE new attributes that do not exist yet
    in the SWArch metamodel. The task is:

      1. Propose the minimal extension to the SWArch metamodel
         (new attributes on SoftwareArchitecture, following the existing
         naming and type conventions in description.txt)

      2. Extend swarch2pim.atl to read those new attributes and generate
         the corresponding PIM elements:
           - deploy_trigger="push:main"  →  PushTrigger with branchGlobs='main'
             on the Pipeline's triggers reference
           - health_check_retries="3"   →  maxAttempts=3 on the healthCheck ScriptJob
           - manual_approval="true"     →  ManualTrigger (or job ifCondition) on push job

      3. Verify which pim2gitlabmodel.atl rules already handle those PIM elements
         correctly (they exist but are dead code today) and which need extending.

  WHY THOSE THREE NEW ATTRIBUTES:
    - deploy_trigger: a string encoding "event:branch", e.g. "push:main"
      Follows the pattern of existing string attributes (unit_test, health_check).
      When non-empty, swarch2pim should create a PushTrigger in the PIM.

    - health_check_retries: a string (not integer, to match EString convention
      used throughout SWArch). When non-empty and numeric, sets maxAttempts on
      the healthCheck job. The PIM Job.maxAttempts is EIntegerObject.

    - manual_approval: "true"/"false" string (consistent with how other flags
      are encoded in SWArch as strings, not booleans).
      When "true" and type=framework, marks the push job as requiring manual trigger.

  WHAT THE AI MUST DISCOVER IN pim2gitlabmodel.atl (dead code audit):
    - createTriggerRule: already handles PushTrigger → '$CI_COMMIT_BRANCH == "main"'
      This will WORK if swarch2pim correctly creates a PushTrigger. No change needed.

    - createWorkflow: already appends trigger rules when pipeline.triggers is non-empty.
      This will WORK automatically. No change needed.

    - createRetry: already maps maxAttempts-1 to GitLabMM!Retry.max.
      The wiring in createJob already calls thisModule.createRetry when maxAttempts > 1.
      This will WORK if swarch2pim sets maxAttempts. No change needed.

    - ManualTrigger on a job: this is where pim2psm MAY need extension.
      A pipeline-level ManualTrigger maps to 'when: manual' in workflow rules (handled).
      A job-level manual gate in GitLab CI maps to 'when: manual' on the job itself.
      The LLM must decide: does the PIM Job.ifCondition or a ManualTrigger in the
      pipeline triggers list better model a job-level manual gate? And does pim2psm
      need a new branch to emit 'when: manual' on the push job specifically?

  THE TEST:
    A weak AI will fail to notice the attributes are new and will just write ATL
    that uses them as if they already exist in the metamodel.

    A strong AI will:
      a) Identify the metamodel gap first
      b) Propose the new attributes (EString type, optional cardinality)
      c) Write swarch2pim ATL that guards on non-empty/non-null values
         (following the pattern: not self.health_check.oclIsUndefined() and self.health_check <> '')
      d) Confirm which pim2psm rules already work and which need changes
      e) Explain the manual_approval mapping decision with ATL reasoning
-->
<swarch:SoftwareArchitecture xmi:version="2.0"
  xmlns:xmi="http://www.omg.org/XMI"
  xmlns:swarch="http://www.mddoai.com/mddoai/metamodel/swarch"
  name="production-payment-api"
  type="framework"
  build_system="docker"
  language="python"
  unit_test="pytest -v --cov=src --cov-report=xml"
  health_check="./scripts/health_check.sh"
  lint_check="pylint src/"
  deploy_trigger="push:main"
  health_check_retries="3"
  manual_approval="true"/>
